Compiled queries fail with uncorrelated parameterized collections

In compiled queries, we don't perform client evaluation over uncorrelated expressions (which don't reference database objects) like we do in regular queries. This means we get queries with primitive collections where the elements are never compared to some other column, and therefore we have no way of inferring the collection's type mapping:

```c#
Func<ApplicationDbContext, string[], IAsyncEnumerable<Currency>> func
    = EF.CompileAsyncQuery((ApplicationDbContext context, string[] search) => context.Currencies.Where(e => search.Any()));
_ = await func(context, []).ToListAsync();

// Non-compiled version works:
// string[] search = [];
// _ = await context.Currencies.Where(e => search.Any()).ToListAsync();
```

This causes e.g. an exception in RelationalTypeMappingPostprocessor.ApplyTypeMappingsOnValuesExpression.

 would make us perform client evaluation over uncorrelated expressions, so they'd behave like non-compiled queries; at that point, `search.Any()` would be evaluated client-side and we'd no longer end up with a collection. However, that issue is complex, and at least in theory we could have such cases in the tree for other reasons.

Originally raised by @Enderlook in https://github.com/PomeloFoundation/Pomelo.EntityFrameworkCore.MySql/issues/2023.

<details>
<summary>Full minimal repro</summary>

